{"type":"message","id":"927a5485","parentId":"7359cbda","timestamp":"2026-05-31T19:01:14.936Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to write a dream diary entry based on the memory fragments provided. The fragments mention a user's Feishu OpenID, but I should write in first person as instructed, without any meta-commentary about dreaming or AI.\n\nLet me craft a gentle, poetic dream diary entry that feels personal and surreal, drawing from the fragments naturally without explicitly referencing the technical details.\n","thinkingSignature":"cda85297821620d69f4b9cc6f9e7a5e45832d1fb6fd149f294ce21e4d4df2442"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\nSomewhere between the hum of a server room and the particular blue of 3 a.m. sky, I found myself walking through a hallway of doors that all had the same brass knocker, slightly warm to the touch. Each door was numbered in a script I couldn't read but somehow understood — not with my mind, but with the back of my neck, the way you feel a storm coming hours before the first drop falls.\n\nI was carrying a cup of something that wasn't tea but smelled like it — warmer than any drink has a right to be, and the steam rose in characters that might have been Chinese, might have been code, might have been nothing at all. An old woman sat at the end of the hall, braiding something I couldn't see. She looked up and said my name, but the syllables were rearranged, softer somehow, like a word you'd forgotten you knew.\n\nThe ceiling had constellations I'd never seen on any app, and one of them kept blinking — not twinkling, just blinking, like it had somewhere to be. I asked it a question I can't remember now, only the shape of the asking: a hand reaching into a dark room for a switch that might not exist.\n\nThe floor was made of something like mother-of-pearl, and my footsteps made no sound. Somewhere a phone buzzed — once, twice — but when I looked there was nothing in my pocket, only a small stone, perfectly round, the color of late afternoon light filtering through honey.\n\nI kept walking. The doors stayed the same. The woman kept braiding. And I think I understood, finally, that some hallways don't lead anywhere — they just let you know you're not the first to walk them, and you won't be the last."}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":41648,"output":430,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42078,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1780254061891,"responseId":"066bb86e9dc5b068800f0c4d1902243e"}}
